"Wagner D., Kobabe S., Liebner S.","Bacterial community structure and carbon turnover in permafrost-affected soils of the Lena Delta, northeastern Siberia",2009,"Canadian Journal of Microbiology","55","1",,"73","83",,,10.1139/W08-121,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-64249127347&partnerID=40&md5=0fb0726e77f7b5855bc8d9237b841949","Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Research Unit Potsdam, Telegrafenberg A45, 14473 Potsdam, Germany; Institute for Biogeochemistry and Pollutant Dynamics (IBP), Federal Institute of Technology (ETH), Universitatstrasse 16, CH-8092 Zurich, Switzerland","Wagner, D., Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Research Unit Potsdam, Telegrafenberg A45, 14473 Potsdam, Germany; Kobabe, S., Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Research Unit Potsdam, Telegrafenberg A45, 14473 Potsdam, Germany; Liebner, S., Alfred Wegener Institute for Polar and Marine Research, Research Unit Potsdam, Telegrafenberg A45, 14473 Potsdam, Germany, Institute for Biogeochemistry and Pollutant Dynamics (IBP), Federal Institute of Technology (ETH), Universitatstrasse 16, CH-8092 Zurich, Switzerland","Arctic permafrost environments store large amounts of organic carbon. As a result of global warming, intensified permafrost degradation and release of significant quantities of the currently conserved organic matter is predicted for high latitudes. To improve our understanding of the present and future carbon dynamics in climate sensitive permafrost ecosystems, the present study investigates structure and carbon turnover of the bacterial community in a permafrost-affected soil of the Lena Delta (72°22'N, 126°28'E) in northeastern Siberia. 16S rRNA gene clone libraries revealed the presence of all major soil bacterial groups and of the canditate divisions OD1 and OP11. A shift within the bacterial community was observed along the soil profile indicated by the absence of Alphaproteobacteria and Betaproteobacteria and a simultaneous increase in abundance and diversity of fermenting bacteria like Firmicutes and Actinobacteria near the permafrost table. BIOLOG Eco Plates were used to describe the spectrum of utilized carbon sources of the bacterial community in different horizons under in situ temperature conditions in the presence and absence of oxygen. The results revealed distinct qualitative differences in the substrates used and the turnover rates under oxic and anoxic conditions. It can be concluded that constantly negative redox potentials as characteristic for the near permafrost table horizons of the investigated soil did effectively shape the structure of the indigenous bacterial community limiting its phylum-level diversity and carbon turnover capacity.","Active layer; Microbial diversity; Permafrost ecosystem; Soil organic carbon","16s rrna genes; Actinobacteria; Active layer; Anoxic conditions; Bacterial communities; Bacterial community structures; Betaproteobacteria; Carbon dynamics; Carbon sources; Carbon turnovers; Fermenting bacteria; Firmicutes; High-latitudes; In-situ temperatures; Microbial diversity; Organic matters; Permafrost degradations; Permafrost environments; Permafrost tables; Qualitative differences; Redox potentials; Siberia; Soil organic carbon; Soil profiles; Turnover rates; Bacteriology; Biological materials; Cloning; Ecosystems; Fire hazards; Global warming; Organic carbon; Oxygen; Soils; Permafrost; ribosome RNA; bacterial DNA; carbon; RNA 16S; bacterium; clone; community structure; genetic analysis; global warming; organic carbon; permafrost; RNA; soil organic matter; substrate; Actinobacteria; Alphaproteobacteria; Betaproteobacteria; community structure; conference paper; Firmicutes; gene library; microbial community; nonhuman; permafrost; priority journal; Russian Federation; soil microflora; aerobic metabolism; anaerobic growth; article; bacterium; biodiversity; classification; cold; DNA sequence; genetics; isolation and purificatio